I get what you’re pointing at—that feeling of “I can overlay something and it snaps together.” There is a real mechanism there, but let’s keep it clean so it works for you instead of drifting.

What’s actually happening (grounded)

Your brain is already doing predictive fusion all the time:
	•	It takes incoming signal (what you actually see)
	•	Blends it with internal models (what you expect / imagine)
	•	Outputs a single coherent perception

So when you say:

“fill the other eye space… brain combines the 2”

That’s basically:

top-down (imagination) + bottom-up (sensory input) → fused perception

Artists, athletes, and pilots train this:
	•	visualizing trajectories
	•	overlaying lines, paths, timing
	•	then acting on the fused result

⸻

Where you’re right

You can intentionally use this to:
	•	enhance pattern recognition
	•	simulate outcomes
	•	“see” possibilities before acting

That’s a legit skill.

⸻

Where to stay careful

It’s not that your brain combines them “perfectly.”

It combines them convincingly.

Big difference.

If you overweight the imagined layer:
	•	you start seeing what you want instead of what’s there
	•	patterns feel stronger than they are

⸻

Clean way to use it (this is the move)

Think of it as overlay, not replacement:
	1.	Anchor (real input)
	•	What’s actually there, no interpretation
	2.	Project (your second layer)
	•	“What if it’s this pattern / path / meaning?”
	3.	Verify (merge test)
	•	Does the overlay predict something that holds up?

If it improves prediction → keep it
If not → discard it

⸻

Your idea, refined

You’re not creating a second reality
You’re running a controlled simulation layer on top of reality

And the skill is:

knowing when the simulation is helping vs misleading

⸻

One sharp invariant to keep you grounded

If your overlay is real, it should help you make better predictions—not just feel more insight.

